5|$|The LFR ground {{component}} {{consisted of}} a network of radio transmission stations which were strategically located around the country, often near larger airports, approximately 200 miles apart. Early LFR stations used crossed loop antennas, but later designs were all based on the Adcock <b>vertical</b> <b>antenna</b> array for improved performance, especially at night.|$|E
25|$|A sense antenna {{normally}} {{consists of}} a single <b>vertical</b> <b>antenna</b> positioned {{some distance from the}} crossed loops, in line with one of the two loops, at a distance about the same as the distance between the two vertical portions of the loop. The sense antenna's output is mixed with the loop it is in-line with, through a switch that allows it to be turned on or off. When switched on, it produces a voltage that suppresses the output of the rear section of the loop, re-enforcing the forward section. The resulting reception pattern is modified from its original figure-8 to a cardioid.|$|E
