5000|$|... #Caption: RF current {{distributions}} (red) in a <b>vertical</b> <b>antenna</b> (a) and the T antenna (b), {{showing how}} the horizontal wire serves {{to improve the}} efficiency of the vertical radiating wire. [...] The width of the red area perpendicular to the wire at any point is proportional to the current. At resonance the current is the tail part of a sinusoidal standing wave. In the <b>vertical</b> <b>antenna</b> (a), the current must go to zero at the top. In the T (b), the current flows into the horizontal wire, increasing the current in the top part of the vertical wire. The radiation resistance and thus the radiated power in each, is proportional to the square of the area of the vertical part of the current distribution.|$|E
